        "guidedSolution": "**Step 1: Understand what rate of change means**\nThe rate of change of the amount of Fermium at time $t$ is given by $\\frac{dP}{dt}$, where $P(t) = 100 \\cdot e^{-6.896 \\times 10^{-3} \\cdot t}$.\n\n**Step 2: Find the derivative**\nThe rate of change function is:\n$$\\frac{dP}{dt} = \\frac{d}{dt}\\left(100 \\cdot e^{-6.896 \\times 10^{-3} \\cdot t}\\right)$$\n\nBy the chain rule:\n$$\\frac{dP}{dt} = 100 \\cdot (-6.896 \\times 10^{-3}) \\cdot e^{-6.896 \\times 10^{-3} \\cdot t}$$\n$$= -0.6896 \\cdot e^{-6.896 \\times 10^{-3} \\cdot t}$$\n\n**Step 3: Evaluate at t = 434.4159329 using CAS**\n\n**Method 1 - Using derivative evaluation:**\n\n**Formula:** $\\frac{d}{dt}\\left(100 \\cdot e^{-6.896 \\times 10^{-3} \\cdot t}\\right)$ at $t = 434.4159329$\n\n**Substitution:** $\\frac{d}{dt}(100 \\cdot e^{-6.896\\text{E-}3 \\cdot t})|_{t=434.4159329}$\n\n**CAS answer:** $-0.03448000001$ grams per day\n\n**Method 2 - Alternative calculation:**\nSince at $t = 434.42$ days, $P \\approx 5$ grams, we can use:\n$$\\frac{dP}{dt} = k \\cdot P = (-6.896 \\times 10^{-3}) \\times 5 = -0.03448$$\n\n**Step 4: Interpret the result**\nThe negative sign indicates the mass is decreasing, which makes sense for radioactive decay.\n\n**Final answer:** The rate of change is approximately $-0.0345$ grams per day (or $-0.03448$ g/day).\n\n---\n\n**Note from examiner:** \"This question was answered well by candidates, with many using their CAS calculator to solve simple calculations with the exponential function. The main errors were in not rounding to three significant figures in part (a) or determining the rate of change in part (c).\"\n\n**This comment clarified:** Students should pay careful attention to rounding requirements - in part (a), the answer must be stated to three significant figures as explicitly requested. In part (c), students needed to recognise that \"rate of change\" means finding the derivative $\\frac{dP}{dt}$ and evaluating it at the specific time from part (b). Simply stating the value of $P$ at that time, or finding the average rate of change, would not earn full marks.",
