        "guidedSolution": "**Step 1: Understand the transformation**\nThe new cost is: (old cost \u00c3\u2014 1.2) + 1\nThis is a linear transformation of the form $Y_{\\text{new}} = 1.2Y + 1$.\n\n**Step 2: Apply the transformation to the mean**\nFor a linear transformation $aY + b$:\n- New mean = $a \\times \\text{old mean} + b$\n\n$$E(Y_{\\text{new}}) = 1.2 \\times 8.875 + 1 = 10.65 + 1 = 11.65$$\n\n**Step 3: Apply the transformation to the standard deviation**\nFor a linear transformation $aY + b$:\n- New standard deviation = $|a| \\times \\text{old standard deviation}$\n- (Adding a constant doesn't affect standard deviation)\n\n$$\\sigma_{\\text{new}} = 1.2 \\times 1.747 \\approx 2.10$$\n\n**Step 4: State the answer**\nThe new mean is approximately **\\$11.65** and the new standard deviation is approximately **\\$2.10**.",
        "topic": "Discrete random variables",
