        "guidedSolution": "**Step 1: Consider the limitations of the normal distribution**\nThe normal distribution extends from $-\\infty$ to $+\\infty$, allowing for negative values.\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the probability of negative weights**\nUsing CAS with $X \\sim N(3, 1)$:\n$$P(X < 0) \\approx 0.00135$$\n\n**Step 3: Explain why this is problematic**\nAlthough this probability is small (about 0.135%), it means the model predicts a non-zero probability of negative weights, which is physically impossible.\n\n**Step 4: State the conclusion**\nThe normal distribution is not a good model because it assigns a non-zero probability to negative weights ($P(X < 0) \\approx 0.00135$), but weights cannot be negative in reality.\n\n---\n\n**Note from examiner:** \"Many candidates [were] not recognising that negative values were involved, or those who did recognise this, failing to calculate probability.\"\n\n**This comment clarified:** When evaluating whether a distribution is appropriate for modelling real-world data, always consider the theoretical range of the distribution versus the practical constraints of the data. The normal distribution has support on $(-\\infty, \\infty)$, which includes negative values. For variables that must be non-negative (like weights, heights, times), check $P(X < 0)$ to demonstrate this limitation. Even a small probability of impossible values indicates the model is not ideal.",
